# Corrected Response

Research suggests that remote work can improve productivity and employee satisfaction for some individuals and organizations. However, the results vary depending on factors such as job type, management practices, collaboration needs, work environment, and individual preferences.

Some studies have reported productivity gains or cost savings in specific contexts, while others have found little difference or identified challenges related to communication, collaboration, and employee well-being.

Rather than relying on a single percentage, it is more accurate to conclude that the effectiveness of remote work depends on the organization, the role, and how remote work is implemented.

---

# Reflection

## What I Learned

Statistics can make AI responses appear highly credible, even when the numbers are completely fabricated. Exact percentages, survey sizes, and averages should not be accepted without verifying their source and methodology.

---

## What I'd Do Differently

When evaluating AI-generated statistics, I would check whether the response identifies the original source, explains how the data was collected, and avoids presenting estimates as universal facts.

